        translations: {
            en: {
                title: 'Modern Apostles and Prophets: Living Proof of God’s Love',
                excerpt: 'Prophets? Now? It’s an incredible idea, isn’t it? The concept of living prophets in Christianity today...',
                content: `<p>Prophets? Now? It’s an incredible idea, isn’t it? The concept of living prophets in Christianity today is a bold claim. But it’s also a beautiful one.</p>

<p>Think about it. If God is the same yesterday, today, and forever, and if He loves us as much as He loved the people in the Bible, why wouldn’t He speak to us now? We face challenges that Moses and Peter never imagined. We have questions unique to our time. Doesn’t it make sense that a loving Father would continue to guide His children?</p>

<p>The truth is, He does.</p>

<p>I want to share why I believe in living prophets and apostles, not just as a doctrinal point, but as a reality that has anchored my life.</p>

<h2>A Pattern of Love</h2>

<p>Throughout history, whenever God has had a people on earth, He has sent prophets to guide them. From Adam to Noah, Abraham to Moses, this has been His pattern. As the Bible says, "Surely the Lord God will do nothing, but he revealeth his secret unto his servants the prophets" (<a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/ot/amos/3?lang=eng&id=p7#p7">Amos 3:7</a>).</p>

<p>When Jesus Christ came to earth, He established His Church. He didn’t just leave a book; He called twelve apostles. He gave them authority to teach, to baptize, and to lead. He built His Church on the "foundation of the apostles and prophets, Jesus Christ himself being the chief corner stone" (<a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/nt/eph/2?lang=eng&id=p20#p20">Ephesians 2:20</a>).</p>

<p>Why would that foundation be removed? If anything, we need it more today, not less.</p>

<h2>Witnesses of Christ</h2>

<p>The primary role of an apostle is to be a special witness of the name of Jesus Christ in all the world. This doesn’t mean they just teach about Him (though they do). It means they speak from a personal knowledge of His reality and His divinity.</p>

<p>In a world that is increasingly secular, confused, and cynical, hearing a voice of certain testimony is piercing. When I hear the apostles today testify of the Savior, I feel a confirmation in my own heart that He lives. Their words point me to Him. They don’t ask for followers for themselves; they ask us to follow Him.</p>

<h2>Guidance for Our Day</h2>

<p>One of the most comforting aspects of having living prophets is knowing that we are not left to figure out modern complexities alone. The Bible is the word of God, but it doesn’t explicitly mention AI, social media, the specific breakdown of the modern family, or the unique anxieties of the 21st century.</p>

<p>Living prophets apply eternal truths to our specific circumstances. They warn us of dangers we might not see. They encourage us when we feel overwhelmed.</p>

<p>For example, in recent years, we’ve been counseled to "Think Celestial"—to view our lives from an eternal perspective. We’ve been urged to "Let God Prevail" in our lives. We’ve been taught how to find peace in a turbulent world. These aren’t just catchy slogans; they are spiritual lifelines that have helped me navigate real struggles.</p>

<h2>They Are Imperfect Men Called by a Perfect God</h2>

<p>Sometimes people struggle with the idea of prophets because they see that these men are human. They are. They get sick, they age, they have personalities. Peter was impetuous. Jonah ran away. Moses had a stutter.</p>

<p>But God has always worked through imperfect people. That’s actually encouraging to me. If God can use them, maybe He can use me, too. The miracle isn’t that they are perfect; the miracle is that God speaks through them despite their imperfections.</p>

<h2>How to Know for Yourself</h2>

<p>You don’t have to take my word for it. In fact, you shouldn’t. The beauty of the gospel of Jesus Christ is that it invites personal revelation.</p>

<p>You can listen to these men. You can read their words. And then you can ask God if they are His messengers. Jesus gave us a test for prophets: "By their fruits ye shall know them" (<a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/nt/matt/7?lang=eng&id=p20#p20">Matthew 7:20</a>).</p>

<p>What are the fruits of following their counsel? For me, the fruits have been peace, a stronger marriage, a clearer sense of purpose, and a deeper relationship with Jesus Christ. When I follow their teachings, I am a better man, husband, and father.</p>

<h2>An Invitation</h2>

<p>Twice a year, in April and October, we have a general conference where we hear from the prophet and apostles. It is available to everyone, everywhere, for free. I invite you to tune in. Listen with an open heart. See if you don’t feel something—a peace, a clarity, a sense of being known by God.</p>

<p>God is not silent. He loves us today just as much as He ever has. And because He loves us, He has sent watchmen on the tower to guide us home.</p>

<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>

<div class="footnote">
<p>If you want to learn more about the current prophet and apostles, you can read their biographies and their recent messages <a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/learn/quorum-of-the-twelve-apostles?lang=eng">here</a>.</p>
</div>`
            }
        }
